Just some random ideas:
Make them keep humans very separated from other humans. To the extent that it's not uncommon for some people to go their whole lives only seeing a few other humans up close and in person. Serious corporal punishment to the hands for humans who step out of line. Smell tracking and smell inspections. General lack of privacy or many rights. Have hyenas be more or less the leaders of the society. That'll allow for it to be a /hmofa/ story much more easily and believably. Have humans have little protection under the law (aside from legitimately serious offenses of bodily harm) unless they abide by very certain and highly restrictive rules and regulations. Have "rewards" for going along with the party. Make the rewards be them giving back some very select few rights that we take for granted. Arranged marriages at a certain age as the default with them being arranged between the state and anthros with no input from the humans. Have one of the highest rewards be getting to decide who you marry. Having that dangling in front of a human's face while they grow up would greatly encourage them to play along.

>>36995935
unlikely, Carcinisation appears to be a product of the twin constraints of exoskeletons and fluid dynamics. There's only so many form factors for a little armored critter to get around in water efficiently.

Opposable thumbs appear to be a product of arboreal life, which requires trees to exist. Bipedalism is really rare and only humans do it in it's true form without using a tail as a third appendage like a kangaroo or regularly walking on all fours like apes and bears. Intelligence appears to be derived from social predatory animals. A big part of intelligence is developing theory of mind, prey animals just have to be good at escaping, whereas predators have to be good at predicting what prey will do, and if the predators are social they have to be good at anticipating what the rest of the pack will do in response to the prey as well. The cognitive load clearly increases along those behavioral lines.

There are other high IQ animals that don't fit that category; corvids, octopi, and elephants for example. But the most consistently intelligent animals are pack hunters so that seems to be a much more reliable way to evolve the trait.

One thing you might want to make use of is having them use humans for much more than just breeding. For example as blacksmiths. In a world where everything has to be crafted by hand, humans, having high dexterity and intelligence, would be extremely valuable. It would allow other species less inclined towards craftsmanship to gain a potentially massive upper hand. They could kidnap humans and force them to become blacksmiths to forge high quality weapons and armor. And that's not even speaking of how much more of an imposing force they'd become against others besides themselves. An enormous, musclebound, hyena warrior would be a threat to a small group of well-armed and armored men. An enormous, musclebound, hyena warrior that has nigh impenetrable armor and a proper weapon would practically be a one person army.
So be careful not to make them too powerful, else there might be no stopping them.
